# Agent Workflow Boundaries

## Planned-Work Lifecycle

For **planned work** (features, refactors, or other tasks that will change code and produce
SDDs), follow this agent chain in order when each step applies:

1. **`code-investigator`** — when existing behaviour or architecture must be understood first.
2. **`architect-planner`** — clarifies vague requirements and produces a phased plan under
   `docs/sdd/<slug>.md`; creates or updates ADRs under `docs/adr/` when the work introduces
   durable architectural decisions.
3. **`phase-executor`** — implements one approved phase per pass.
4. **`doc-sync`** — syncs implementation status back into the planning doc immediately after execution.
5. **`test-runner`** — reviews diff, adds/updates tests, runs verification, writes test report.
6. **`doc-sync`** again — syncs verification status, coverage, and residual risk into the planning doc.
7. **`rule-feedback-writer`** — persists any durable guidance changes raised during the above steps.
8. **Pull request** — merge the feature via PR using the description template in
   `pull-request-requirements.mdc` (one PR per feature, not per commit).

Do not run the full chain for read-only Q&A, investigations, or other tasks with no planned
code change.

## Standalone Subagent Use

The lifecycle above governs **planned work only**. Individual subagents may be spawned whenever
the task benefits from specialised, focused work — not only as steps in that chain.

| Subagent | Standalone when |
| --- | --- |
| **`code-investigator`** | Read-only questions: "how does X work?", API or flow overviews, log-backed traces. Produces `docs/investigation/<slug>.md` when a durable report is useful. |
| **`architect-planner`** | Vague or large scope that needs a phased plan before any implementation. |
| **`phase-executor`**, **`test-runner`**, **`doc-sync`**, **`rule-feedback-writer`** | Planned work only — these mutate code, tests, plans, or durable guidance. |

The parent agent decides whether to answer inline or spawn a subagent based on scope, complexity,
and whether a durable artifact is warranted. Narrow, specific questions may be answered directly
with read/grep tools; broad, ambiguous, or cross-cutting questions should prefer a read-only
subagent (e.g. **`code-investigator`**, **`explore`**) rather than skipping delegation because
the task is not planned work.

## Handoff Rules

Follow these handoffs for the **planned-work lifecycle**. For **standalone** subagents, apply the
same handoffs only when the task requires it (e.g. linking an investigation report into an
existing SDD, or syncing a one-off implementation back to a plan).

- After `phase-executor` completes, hand off to `doc-sync` **before** verification so the
  planning doc captures implementation status, changed files, risks, pending work, and next phase.
- Optional: `.cursor/hooks.json` `subagentStop` hooks auto-submit a follow-up to invoke `doc-sync`
  after `phase-executor` and again after `test-runner` (see `workflow-hooks.mdc`).
- After that doc sync, hand off to `test-runner` to review the diff, add/update tests, run
  verification, and write a test execution report under `docs/sdd/test-reports/`.
- After `test-runner` writes the report, hand off to `doc-sync` again to sync verification
  status, coverage, failures, and residual risk back into the planning doc.

## Parallelisation Policy

- Parallelise **thinking and read-only analysis** only.
- Never parallelise writes to product code, tests, config, reports, plan files, or ADRs.
- Use fast models for parallel read-only subagents.
- Keep final code, test, config, report, and plan-file edits **single-writer**.

## Responsibility Boundaries

- `phase-executor` must not create or update planning docs, execution notes, test reports, or ADRs.
- `architect-planner` must not implement application code, tests, or configuration.
- `architect-planner` should record durable cross-cutting decisions in `docs/adr/` (see
  `architectural-decisions.mdc`), not only in SDDs under `docs/sdd/`.
- `doc-sync` must not modify product code or tests unless explicitly instructed.
- `test-runner` must not claim tests passed without real command output evidence.
- `rule-feedback-writer` must not persist one-off or task-specific facts.

## Guidance Placement

- `AGENTS.md` — broad defaults for all agents (optional, in the consuming repo).
- `.cursor/agents/*.mdc` — role-specific workflow and responsibility guidance (this repo); keep
  tech-stack agnostic.
- `.cursor/rules/<category>/*.mdc` — enforceable constraints grouped by scope (see
  `rule-placement.mdc`): `agent/` for workflow, `language/` for language best practices,
  `<framework-slug>/` (e.g. `node24/`) for stack-specific rules. Optional standards from sibling
  repos (e.g. [genai_node_rules](https://github.com/genai/genai_node_rules),
  [genai_ts_rules](https://github.com/genai/genai_ts_rules),
  [genai_js_rules](https://github.com/genai/genai_js_rules)) merge into the matching category
  in consuming repos.
- `docs/adr/*.md` — durable architectural decisions (patterns, trade-offs, boundaries, stack
  and cross-cutting workflow choices) for consuming repos; see `architectural-decisions.mdc`.
- Keep feature-specific API details, endpoint matrices, incident notes, and one-off facts in
  planning, execution, test-report, or investigation docs — not in agent or rule files.
